<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Working from home</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean the basic s=
ituation in investment banking is that if you are a junior analyst and you =
are in the office fewer than like 80 hours a week, you will be in trouble, =
while if you are a senior managing director and you=E2=80=99re in the offic=
e more than like 20 hours a week you will be in trouble. Analysts are expec=
ted to show up by 10ish, look busy and be available for eight hours, order =
dinner, and then settle in=C2=A0for a long night of building models and tur=
ning pitchbooks. If you=E2=80=99re not around and available all day, and cr=
anking on Excel all night, you are not doing your job.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">MDs, meanwhile, are expected to get on planes and go meet with =
clients to win new business. Of course=C2=A0sometimes they need to be in th=
e office to supervise and motivate their underlings, to tell them what page=
s they want in the pitchbook, etc. Other times they will do client meetings=
 by telephone or videoconference; it happens. But in general if you are sit=
ting around your office all day, instead of your clients=E2=80=99 offices, =
you are not doing the highest-value-add part of your job.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Obviously this was upended by the pandemic. But in different=
 ways. Analysts lost a lot of learning and mentorship and social opportunit=
ies: Instead of hanging out with other 23-year-olds and learning Excel shor=
tcuts and financial-modeling techniques and where to find the good pitchboo=
k pages, they had to muddle through their work on their own, which took lon=
ger and was less satisfying. Instead of sitting in the MD=E2=80=99s office =
to listen to client calls, with the MD occasionally muting her line to expl=
ain what was going on, they churned out pitchbooks alone at home. Instead o=
f ordering dinner to the office and joking around with their friends, they =
ate dinner at home while working quietly and sadly. Sure they didn=E2=80=99=
t have to commute, but their commute from Murray Hill wasn=E2=80=99t that l=
ong anyway, and their apartments aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0that nice. Perhaps the=
y have moved back in with their parents, which is a decidedly mixed bag.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the MDs, freed from the need to com=
mute to the office, can work from their much nicer Hamptons houses. They do=
n=E2=80=99t need to get on planes four times a week to meet with clients; t=
hey can just do everything from home and then go to the beach. Perhaps they=
 are learning less from the serendipity and in-person interactions of being=
 in the office, but they were pretty far up the learning curve already. Als=
o, remember, they just weren=E2=80=99t in the office that much to begin wit=
h; they were always on planes to meet with clients so the serendipity was l=
imited.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now the pandemic measures are endin=
g and banks are going back to work. If you are a junior banker that=E2=80=
=99s mostly good; you can see your friends and learn stuff and not work out=
 of your bedroom. If you are a senior banker that means getting back on pla=
nes and going to see clients, which is exhausting, but also frankly if you=
=E2=80=99ve made it to a senior job at an investment bank that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the social aspects of the job, meeting with potential clients and trying=
 to befriend them and understand their business in person =E2=80=94=C2=A0is=
 probably something you enjoy. But when you get back from a client trip lat=
e Tuesday night, and you=E2=80=99ve got another trip planned Thursday morni=
ng, and the bank wants you back in the office on Wednesday to sit at your d=
esk =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>feels=C2=A0unnecessary now, doesn=E2=
=80=99t it? If you=E2=80=99ve got a day between trips to catch up on emails=
 and phone calls, you=E2=80=99d rather spend it at your Hamptons house than=
 schlepping into the office.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
d3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qcG1vcmdhbi1nb2xkbWFuLWNhbGwtdGltZS1vbi13b3JrLWZyb20=
taG9tZS10aGVpci1yaXZhbHMtYXJlLXJlYWR5LXRvLXBvdW5jZS0xMTYyNTU2MzgwMD9tb2Q9aH=
BfbGVhZF9wb3M2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb894d3da" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a growing divide on Wall Street: firms callin=
g employees back and firms telling people they can work from home.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Titans like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and JPMorgan C=
hase &amp; Co. are taking a hard-line approach, beefing up in-person staff =
five days a week in New York even though it might mean losing talent. Rival=
s including Citigroup Inc. are touting flexibility, betting that a softer a=
pproach will help them poach top traders and deal makers. =E2=80=A6</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Culture is at the heart of the debate. Some say th=
e trading floor is the last bastion of Wall Street, where interns and young=
 employees learn by osmosis. Others think record results in a remote-work y=
ear prove that the trading floor and the office alike have lost their relev=
ance.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My model is that, in the=
 short term, more work-from-home is probably the good trade: =E2=80=9CRecor=
d results in a remote-work year=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>prove that y=
ou can do it successfully for a time, using primarily bankers and traders w=
hom you=E2=80=99ve already trained and acculturated in the office.[2] And s=
enior bankers and traders=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>prefer to work from their=
 Hamptons houses, so you can keep your senior bankers and poach your compet=
itors=E2=80=99 if you=E2=80=99re more flexible.=C2=A0But in the long run yo=
u want your junior bankers and traders to be trained, at the office, by the=
 senior bankers and traders, and it=E2=80=99s hard to do that if all of the=
 senior people are at home all the time.=C2=A0</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight:=
